descriptionV3.text: JavaScript frameworks and libraries keep growing, sprouting increasingly more dependencies along the way. Svelte—a new, lightweight component framework—marches into this tangle with a brush cutter, trimming down the weeds to provide a core set of key functionalities with zero dependencies. In this course, join Ray Villalobos as he helps you get up to speed with Svelte, explaining how to use it to create apps that please your users without making them wait. Learn how Svelte differs from frameworks like Angular and React, as well as how to use styles and preprocessors with Svelte, work with data across multiple components, use lifecycle methods to load data, and more.

lines.caption: - [Ray] Hi there, it's Ray again.
Thanks for watching this course.
Svelte has one of the best websites
when you want to learn more information,
including this fantastic step-by-step tutorial
on how to use Svelte.
It's really good.
It's called the REPL,
and I think it's pretty good
if you want to try out specific features.
I don't think it's as good
if you want to work with projects,
and that's why I made this course.
Now, there's a lot of stuff here in this drop-down,
and you can find out more, for example,
about if blocks.
There's all kinds of event handlers
and modifiers that you can use,
and pretty much everything we cover
plus a lot more in the topics right here.
There's also a detailed documentation
under this API section,
so you can dig into each one
of the different directives here
and learn how to do additional things
that are not in the tutorial.
Now, there's also a place for examples,
which are more kind of realistic examples
that you can take a look at.
The REPL is right here
if you just want to straight-up play around with the code,
and it's pretty well-made.
You can download the code that you use in here,
which will be more of a project-based approach.
There's also the usual blog,
frequently asked questions,
and if you want to learn to build
more complete applications,
the one that you want to use is Sapper,
which is more like a Nuxt or Next.js-type application,
and it's kind of a,
gives you sort of the elements of a framework
for building projects.
There's also a Discord channel
which you can get right here,
and you can go to their GitHub project
right in this link.
If you want to learn more about Svelte
or what I'm up to,
you can go to our learning site
and just do a search for my name, Ray Villalobos.
You can find a list of all the courses
that I'm working on.
And if you want to learn more about Svelte,
I'd suggest that you put it in the comments in the feedback.
Now, this course is going to give you a great introduction.
It doesn't go very deep,
and if we get a lot of feedback,
I'll probably add some additional courses on Svelte.
Now, in addition to that,
if you want to learn more about me,
make sure to check out my personal website at Raybo.org.
You have also a list of all the courses
that I'm working on, additional articles,
and links to all of my social media platforms.
You can usually find me just about anywhere @planetoftheweb.
So thanks for watching.
